Feb 27, 2025
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
S.B. 205
SESSION 2025
PRINCIPAL CLERK
S D
SENATE BILL DRS35071-MG-63
Short Title: Clarify Swimming Pool Laws/Priv. Pool Rentals. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Jarvis (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT CLARIFYING THE SCOPE OF SWIMMING POOL LAWS BY AMENDING THE
3 EXEMPTION FOR PRIVATE POOLS SERVING SINGLE FAMILY DWELLINGS; AND
4 MAKING OTHER TECHNICAL CHANGES TO G.S. 130A-280.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. G.S. 130A-280, as amended by Section 4.51 of S.L. 2024-49, reads as
7 rewritten:
8 "§ 130A-280. Scope.Scope and definitions.
9 (a) This Article Part provides for the regulation of public swimming pools in the State as
10 they may affect the public health and safety. As used in this Article, the term "public swimming
11 pool" means any structure, chamber, or tank containing an artificial body of water used by the
12 public for swimming, diving, wading, recreation, or therapy, together with buildings,
13 appurtenances, and equipment used in connection with the body of water, regardless of whether
14 a fee is charged for its use. The term includes municipal, school, hotel, motel, apartment,
15 boarding house, athletic club, or other membership facility pools and spas, spas operating for
16 display at temporary events, and artificial swimming lagoons. As used in this Article, an
17 "artificial swimming lagoon" means any body of water used for recreational purposes with more
18 than 20,000 square feet of surface area, an artificial liner, and a method of disinfectant that results
19 in a disinfectant residual in the swimming zone that is protective of the public health. This Article
20 Part does not apply to any of the following:
21 (1) A private pool serving a single family dwelling and used only by the residents
22 of the dwelling and their guests.guests, regardless of whether their guests gain
23 use of the private pool through a sharing economy platform or pay a fee for
24 its use. In all cases in which a fee is exchanged for access to a private pool
25 serving a single family dwelling that is used only by the residents of the
26 dwelling and their guests, the private pool shall be maintained in good and
27 safe working order.
28 (2) A private pool serving a single family dwelling meeting the minimum
29 requirements of this subdivision which is offered to, and used by, individuals
30 on a temporary basis utilizing a sharing economy platform. For the purposes
31 of this subdivision, a sharing economy platform means an online platform
32 used to facilitate peer-to-peer transactions to acquire, provide, or share access
33 to goods and services. For the purposes of this subdivision, a pool must meet
34 all of the following minimum requirements:
*DRS35071-MG-63*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. Pools must have proper fencing and barriers to prevent unsupervised
2 access, especially by children. The fence should be at least 4 feet high
3 with a self-latching gate.
4 b. Pools must have clear and conspicuous signage posted around the pool
5 area specifying pool rules, depth markers, and any potential hazards.
6 c. Pools must be equipped with basic lifesaving equipment, including life
7 rings and reaching poles.
8 d. Pool decks and surrounding areas must have non-slip surfaces.
9 e. Pools must have properly fitted covers for all submerged suction
10 outlets.
11 f. Pools must be well-maintained with proper chemical balance and
12 cleanliness to ensure safe and healthy swimming conditions.
13 (3) Therapeutic pools used in physical therapy programs operated by medical
14 facilities licensed by the Department or operated by a licensed physical
15 therapist, nor to therapeutic chambers drained, cleaned, and refilled after each
16 individual use.
17 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Part:
18 (1) Artificial swimming lagoon. – Any body of water used for recreational
19 purposes with more than 20,000 square feet of surface area, an artificial liner,
20 and a method of disinfectant that results in a disinfectant residual in the
21 swimming zone that is protective of the public health.
22 (2) Public swimming pool. – Any structure, chamber, or tank containing an
23 artificial body of water used by the public for swimming, diving, wading,
24 recreation, or therapy, together with buildings, appurtenances, and equipment
25 used in connection with the body of water, regardless of whether a fee is
26 charged for its use. The term includes municipal, school, hotel, motel,
27 apartment, boarding house, athletic club, or other membership facility pools
28 and spas, spas operating for display at temporary events, and artificial
29 swimming lagoons.
30 (3) Sharing economy platform. – An online platform used to facilitate
31 peer-to-peer transactions to acquire, provide, or share access to goods and
32 services."
33 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025.
